text=:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a:Essential: {Category.LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild$:essential}%0a:Title: Speaking Mandarin in Hong Kong during the COVID pandemic%0a:Author: vincent_c%0a:Section: C%0a:Completed: 24.04.2021 - 17:36%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210505-022017-211880#%0a* [-04.05.2021 - 19:20-] || TA_lili marked as complete%0a#foxend 210505-022017-211880#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aThis article examines discrimination against Mandarin or other non-Cantonese speakers in Hong Kong after the outbreak of COVID-19%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0ahttps://www.bangkokpost.com/world/1873089/more-than-100-hk-restaurants-refuse-to-serve-customers-from-china%0a%0aThe articles examines the actions taken by over 100 restaurants in Hong Kong at the beginning of the COVID-19 pandemic in March, 2020. These restaurants made public posts and signage refusing service to individuals who spoke Mandarin, the dominant dialect of Chinese (if we ignore the argument that many Chinese dialects could be considered separate languages), as it typically indicates that the individual is from Mainland China and not Hong Kong, where Cantonese is spoken by the majority of the population. %0a%0aMandarin is a dialect that uses four tones, while Cantonese uses six. Additionally, the two dialects pronounce most words drastically differently. The dialect being discriminated against is Mandarin Chinese.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_lili:)
